          aria-label="GitHub"
        >
          <svg viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true">
            <path d="M8 0C3.58 0 0 3.58 0 8c0 3.54 2.29 6.53 5.47 7.59.4.07.55-.17.55-.38 0-.19-.01-.82-.01-1.49-2.01.37-2.53-.49-2.69-.94-.09-.23-.48-.94-.82-1.13-.28-.15-.68-.52-.01-.53.63-.01 1.08.58 1.23.82.72 1.21 1.87.87 2.33.66.07-.52.28-.87.51-1.07-1.78-.2-3.64-.89-3.64-3.95 0-.87.31-1.59.82-2.15-.08-.2-.36-1.02.08-2.12 0 0 .67-.21 2.2.82.64-.18 1.32-.27 2-.27s1.36.09 2 .27c1.53-1.04 2.2-.82 2.2-.82.44 1.1.16 1.92.08 2.12.51.56.82 1.27.82 2.15 0 3.07-1.87 3.75-3.65 3.95.29.25.54.73.54 1.48 0 1.07-.01 1.93-.01 2.2 0 .21.15.46.55.38A8.01 8.01 0 0 0 16 8c0-4.42-3.58-8-8-8z"/>
          </svg>
          <span>GitHub</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/contact" class="lpd-cta">Book a demo</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <nav class="lpd-tabs" aria-label="Docs sections">
      <a href="#introduction" data-tab-link data-top="introduction" class="is-active">Documentation</a>
      <a href="#install" data-tab-link data-top="install">SDK Reference</a>
      <a href="#datasets" data-tab-link data-top="datasets">Platform Guide</a>
      <a href="/blog">Blog</a>
      <a href="/">laceplatform.com ↗</a>
    </nav>
  </header>

  <!-- ── Body: sidebar / content / toc ────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="lpd-body">
    <aside class="lpd-side" aria-label="Docs navigation">
      <div class="lpd-side-quick">
        <a href="/platform/enterprise-search">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><circle cx="10.5" cy="10.5" r="6.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"/><path d="M15.5 15.5L21 21" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"/></svg>
          Platform site
        </a>
        <a href="/blog">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 3.5h14v17H5z" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/><path d="M8.5 8h7M8.5 11.5h7M8.5 15h4.5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/></svg>
          Blog
        </a>
        <a href="/contact">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 7.5A1.5 1.5 0 0 1 5.5 6h13A1.5 1.5 0 0 1 20 7.5v9a1.5 1.5 0 0 1-1.5 1.5h-13A1.5 1.5 0 0 1 4 16.5v-9Z" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/><path d="m5 8 7 5 7-5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/></svg>
          Support
        </a>
      </div>

      {
        sidebar.map((section) => (
          <div class="lpd-side-group" data-side-group>
            <p>{section.group}</p>
            {section.items.map((item) => (
              <a href={`#${item.id}`} data-side-link data-target={item.id}>
                {item.label}
              </a>
            ))}
          </div>
        ))
      }
      <p class="lpd-side-empty" data-side-empty hidden>No matches.</p>
    </aside>

    <main class="lpd-main">
      <!-- Get started -->
      <section id="introduction" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <p class="lpd-crumb">Get Started</p>
        <h1>Introduction</h1>
        <p class="lpd-sub">
          LACE is the AI platform for the governed enterprise — search, knowledge
          graph, agents, and an app builder on one accountability substrate.
          This hub covers the public developer surface.
        </p>

        <div class="lpd-callout">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
            <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <path d="M12 8v.5M12 11v5" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6"/>
          </svg>
          <p>
            Full platform documentation is delivered <strong>in-product</strong> and
            versioned with the release you run. The
            <code class="lp-inline-code">lace-app-sdk</code> below is the public,
            stable surface for developers.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="lpd-cards">
          <a href="/platform/enterprise-search" class="lpd-card">
            <strong>Enterprise Search</strong>
            <span>Cited, permissions-aware answers across every source.</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/platform/knowledge-graph" class="lpd-card">
            <strong>Knowledge Graph</strong>
            <span>Bitemporal facts with receipts and conflict detection.</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/platform/agents" class="lpd-card">
            <strong>Agentic Platform</strong>
            <span>Governed agents on chat, email, SMS, and voice.</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/platform/app-builder" class="lpd-card">
            <strong>App Builder</strong>
            <span>Prompt → sandboxed build → live, versioned application.</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="organization" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>How LACE is organized</h2>
        <p>
          Five peer product surfaces share one control plane: <strong>Pipelines</strong>
          (versioned, typed workflow graphs), <strong>Agents</strong> (tool-using
          definitions with deployments and channels), <strong>Apps</strong>
          (manifest-defined packages), <strong>Knowledge</strong> (datasets,
          retrieval, search, and the knowledge graph), and the
          <strong>Assistant</strong> (a tenant-scoped copilot over the same APIs).
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Every resource and execution is tenant-scoped; roles resolve to named permission scopes.</li>
          <li>Model output proposes; deterministic services enforce permissions, validation, budgets, and approvals.</li>
          <li>Evidence is first-class: retrieval and graph assertions point back to document spans.</li>
          <li>Durable work uses persisted attempts, checkpoints, idempotency, and dead-letter handling.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="deployment" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Deployment options</h2>
        <p>The governance substrate is identical in every footprint.</p>
        <div class="lpd-table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Footprint</th><th>Where it runs</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Managed cloud</strong></td><td>Our cloud</td><td>Fastest start; usage-based AI budgets with hard caps.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Private cloud</strong></td><td>Your VPC</td><td>SSO/OIDC, custom connectors, BYO models.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>On-premises</strong></td><td>Your data center</td><td>Full platform, your hardware and boundary.</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Air-gapped</strong></td><td>Disconnected enclave</td><td>No external AI calls; accreditation evidence exportable.</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- SDK -->
      <section id="install" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <p class="lpd-crumb">lace-app-sdk</p>
        <h1>Install</h1>
        <p class="lpd-sub">
          The public, versioned contract surface for building apps on LACE. A
          facade over the live platform contracts — never a fork of them.
        </p>
        <div class="lp-code">
          <div class="lp-code-head"><span>terminal</span><em>bash</em></div>
          <pre><code set:html={codeInstall} /></pre>
        </div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Facade, not fork</strong> — every symbol re-exports live core contracts; the builder and the sidecar resolve to the same code.</li>
          <li><strong>Stability boundary</strong> — apps import only <code class="lp-inline-code">lace_app_sdk</code>; breaking a published symbol is a major version bump with a deprecation window.</li>
          <li><strong>Governed by construction</strong> — data, tools, routes, and agents flow through platform services with tenancy, policy, and audit applied.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="quickstart" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Quickstart</h2>
        <p>
          An app is a manifest plus providers. Four small files make a governed
          application: the manifest, a data collection, a tool provider, and an
          agent definition.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="manifest" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Manifest</h2>
        <p>
          <code class="lp-inline-code">LaceAppManifest</code> declares everything
          your app provides. LACE discovers manifests and wires providers at
          bootstrap — no registration calls, no glue code.
        </p>
        <div class="lp-code">
          <div class="lp-code-head"><span>app.py</span><em>python</em></div>
          <pre><code set:html={codeManifest} /></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="data" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Data collections</h2>
        <p>
          Collections are typed with JSON Schema and served through the governed
          <code class="lp-inline-code">AppDataService</code> — tenant-scoped,
          audited, with an automatic admin panel. Binary payloads go through
          <code class="lp-inline-code">put_blob</code> /
          <code class="lp-inline-code">get_blob</code>. No raw tables, no policy
          bypass.
        </p>
        <div class="lp-code">
          <div class="lp-code-head"><span>app/data.py</span><em>python</em></div>
          <pre><code set:html={codeData} /></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="tools" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Tools</h2>
        <p>
          Implement <code class="lp-inline-code">AppToolProvider</code> to expose
          custom tools. Tools run in constrained runtimes, and trust tier plus
          permissions are checked before every dispatch.
        </p>
        <div class="lp-code">
          <div class="lp-code-head"><span>app/tools.py</span><em>python</em></div>
          <pre><code set:html={codeTools} /></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="agents" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Agents &amp; skills</h2>
        <p>
          Declare an <code class="lp-inline-code">AgentDefinition</code> and it
          runs a real agentic loop in your sidecar — the model chooses tools;
          the platform enforces capabilities, loop guards, and approval gates.
          Set <code class="lp-inline-code">approval_required=True</code> on a
          capability and every invocation pauses for human sign-off.
        </p>
        <div class="lp-code">
          <div class="lp-code-head"><span>app/agents.py</span><em>python</em></div>
          <pre><code set:html={codeAgents} /></pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section id="modules" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Module reference</h2>
        <div class="lpd-table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Module</th><th>What it gives you</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              {
                modules.map(([name, description]) => (
                  <tr>
                    <td><code class="lp-inline-code">{name}</code></td>
                    <td>{description}</td>
                  </tr>
                ))
              }
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="lpd-note">
          Every app — generated or hand-written — publishes through the same
          audited lifecycle: intent → architect → scaffold → validate → proof
          lanes → seal → publish.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Platform guide -->
      <section id="datasets" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <p class="lpd-crumb">Platform Guide</p>
        <h1>Datasets &amp; connectors</h1>
        <p>
          Datasets are tenant-scoped containers over uploads and live
          connectors — SharePoint, Google Drive, OneDrive, Dropbox, Notion,
          Slack, email, S3, databases, and websites — with scheduled sync,
          change reconciliation, and permission snapshots that flow forward to
          every query.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="search-rag" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Search &amp; RAG</h2>
        <p>
          Hybrid retrieval fuses lexical and vector legs with reciprocal-rank
          fusion, filters by source ACLs, and optionally reranks on GPU.
          Evidence carries stable document, block, and span identity — answers
          open the original passage, and tables stay tables.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="knowledge-graph" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Knowledge graph</h2>
        <p>
          Schema packs are versioned, executable ontology contracts. Extraction
          is candidate-first and evidence-gated; identity resolution merges
          duplicates reversibly; assertions are bitemporal, so corrections
          supersede history instead of erasing it.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="agents-channels" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Agents &amp; channels</h2>
        <p>
          One control plane drives every agent: sessions, tasks, streaming,
          steering, and cancellation. Channels normalize email, SMS, WhatsApp,
          Slack, Teams, webhooks, and realtime voice — with consent, delivery
          retries, human handoff, and cost attribution built in.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="workflows" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>Workflows &amp; pipelines</h2>
        <p>
          Pipelines are versioned graphs of typed steps with checkpoints,
          retries, idempotency, and dead-letter handling. Workflow Studio
          compiles the same contract the API executes: drafts, versions,
          triggers, aliases, and a full run timeline.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="app-builder" class="lpd-sec" data-sec>
        <h2>App Builder</h2>
        <p>
          Describe an application and the builder plans it, constructs it in a
